      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "In SceneKit, geometries attached to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects form the visible elements of a scene, and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmaterial"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects attached to a geometry determine its appearance."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Working with Geometry Objects",
          "anchor": "1655044"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "inlineHead",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "You control a geometry’s appearance in a scene with nodes and materials."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " A geometry object provides only the form of a visible object rendered by SceneKit. You specify color and texture for a geometry’s surface, control how it responds to light, and add special effects by attaching materials (for details, see the methods in "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scngeometry#1655143"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "). You position and orient a geometry in a scene by attaching it to an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object. Multiple nodes can reference the same geometry object, allowing it to appear at different positions in a scene."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "inlineHead",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "You can easily copy geometries and change their materials."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " A geometry object manages the association between immutable vertex data and a mutable assignment of materials. To make a geometry appear more than once in the same scene with a different set of materials, use its inherited "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/objectivec/nsobject/1418807-copy"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method. The copy shares the underlying vertex data of the original, but can be assigned materials independently. You can thus make many copies of a geometry without incurring a significant cost to rendering performance."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "inlineHead",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "You can animate a geometry object."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " The vertex data associated with a geometry is immutable, but SceneKit provides several ways to animate geometry. You can use a "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmorpher"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " or "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnskinner"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object to deform a geometry’s surface, or run animations created in an external 3D authoring tool and loaded from a scene file. You can also use methods in the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnshadable"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " protocol to add custom GLSL shader programs that alter SceneKit’s rendering of a geometry. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Obtaining a Geometry Object",
          "anchor": "1655051"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "SceneKit provides several ways to introduce geometry objects to your app:"
